               <msContents>
                  <summary>A nearly complete copy of the <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc"
                        key="work_7215">Fatāvī-yi Birahnah</title> (Unveiled Decrees), a compendium
                     of judicial decrees issued by theologians of the Ḥanafī school, in two volumes
                     bound together. The author, <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="supplied"
                        >Naṣīr al-Dīn bin Imām Lāhūrī (fl. 16th c)</persName>, composed the work in
                     twenty-six chapters (<hi rend="italic">bāb</hi>), of which the first three
                     comprise the first volume (folios <locus from="4a" to="149b">4a to 149b</locus>), and the remainder the second <locus from="150b" to="250b">150b to 250b</locus>. The final chapter
                     presents a long biographical account of the school's founder <persName
                        role="subject" key="person_88126052" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/88126052">Abū
                        Ḥanīfah (d. ca. 767)</persName>, which during the course of composing it,
                     the author relates that he saw the subject in a dream on the night of <date
                        calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1589-02-28">13 Rabī‘ II 997 AH (28 Feb.
                        1589)</date>, followed by brief entries on another 169 Ḥanafī theologians.
                     Two different unidentified, likely Mughal-era scribes, completed the first volume in <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1748-12-22" to="1749-12-10">1162 AH
                        (1748–1749 CE)</date> and the second in <date
                        calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1716-12-05" to="1717-12-09">1129 AH
                        (1716–1717 CE)</date>.</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_750-item1">
                     <author key="person_f1305">
                        <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="supplied">Naṣīr al-Dīn bin Imām
                           Lāhūrī</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="ar">نصیر الدین بن امام لاهوری</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_7215">Fatāvī-yi Birahnah</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_7215">فتاوای برهنه</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_7215" type="alt">Fiqh-i
                        Birahnah</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_7215">فقه برهنه</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa" type="basmala"><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ (folio
                           1b):</locus> حمد مر خدای جهانرا که یکتا است باوصاف کمال و مبرا است از
                        سمات نقص و زوال و صلوات بر رسول او محمد مصطفی صلی الله تعالی علیه و سلم که
                        مبین حلال است و حرام و بر ال و اصحاب او که حامیان دین اند و اعیان اسلام اما
                        بعد این کتابی است… الخ </incipit>
                     <!-- Add Navabpour chapters later, but note TOC below. Double-check folio numbers against image manifest after imaging-->
                     <explicit xml:lang="ar"><locus from="149b" to="149b"> برگ ۱۴۹پ (Folio
                        149b):</locus>
                     </explicit>
                     <colophon><locus from="149b" to="149b"> برگ ۱۴۹پ (Folio 149b):</locus> در دل
                        تمت بعونه ولطفه وتوفیقه وصدقه سنه الف ومائیه <hi rend="strikethrough">تسع و
                           عشرین</hi> تسع واربعین. </colophon>
                     <explicit xml:lang="ar"><locus from="250a" to="250a"> برگ ۲۵۰ر (Folio
                           250a):</locus>
                     </explicit>
                     <colophon><locus from="250a" to="250a"> برگ ۲۵۰ر (Folio 250a):</locus> در دل
                        تمت بعونه ولطفه وتوفیقه وصدقه سنه الف ومائیه <hi rend="strikethrough">تسع و
                           عشرین</hi> تسع واربعین. </colophon>
                     <colophon xml:lang="en">First colophon dated <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1748-12-22" to="1749-12-10">1162 AH
                        (1748–1749 CE)</date> and the second <date
                           calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1716-12-05" to="1717-12-09">1129 AH
                           (1716–1717 CE)</date>, the latter crossed out by another hand, with another another date,
                        twenty years later, written underneath<date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" to="1737-04-19"
                           from="1736-05-12">1149 AH (1736–1737 CE)</date>.</colophon>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <note>Note that in his handlist, Michael Kerney misreads <persName
                           role="subject" key="person_88126052" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/88126052"
                           >Abū Ḥanīfah</persName>'s name as <q xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc">Abū
                           Khaifah</q>. For a detailed overview of the work, its authorship, and
                        contents, work see Ivanow catalogue (ASB 1037).</note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>The first volume written on two types of medium-weight, straight-grained, evenly formed,
                           externally sized and polished henna-tinted <material>paper</material>,
                           probably handmade in the <placeName cert="high"
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208">Indian
                              subcontinent</placeName>, the first with ~10 laid lines per cm. and the second slightly heavier stock, with ~8 laid lines per cm., and neither with
                           discernible chain lines. The second volume written in on comparatively heavy, naturally straw-coloured, flocked, evenly formed, with ~8 laid lines per cm. and no discernible chain lines.
                           externally sized and polished henna-tinted <material>paper</material>, also
                           probably handmade in the <placeName cert="high"
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208">Indian
                              subcontinent</placeName>.</support>

                        <extent><measure unit="folio" quantity="250">250 folios, 4 flyleaves (ff. ii
                              + 250 + ii)</measure>. <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>281</height>
                              <width>160</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>205</height>
                              <width>95</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <!-- Confirm after imaging -->
                        <foliation xml:id="original">Original Hindu-Arabic numerals on the upper-left corners
                           of the a sides.</foliation>
                        <foliation xml:id="modern">Modern pencilled Arabic numerals on the upper-left corners of the initial four then thereafter every tenth folio, referenced in this record. The inconsistent numbers may reflect either miscounting and/or missing folios.</foliation>
                        <collation> Undetermined. <catchwords>Catchwords throughout most of the
                              lower-left corners of the b sides.</catchwords></collation>
                        <condition>Handle text with caution. Water and insect damage and historical
                           repairs throughout.</condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="25" n="mistara"> Written in 1 column with 25
                           lines per page. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">misṭarah</hi> hand
                           guide.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
